Name: Proto-Central Malayo-Polynesian
Description: Central Malayo-Polynesian = the AN languages of the Lesser Sunda islands and the southern and central Moluccas of eastern Indonesia.

Name: Proto-Malayo-Polynesian
Description: Malayo-Polynesian = all AN languages outside Taiwan.

Name: Proto-Oceanic
Description: Oceanic = the roughly 460 AN languages of Melanesia, Micronesia, and Polynesia except Palauan and Chamorro of western Micronesia.

Name: Proto-Western Malayo-Polynesian
Description: Western Malayo-Polynesian = the AN languages of the Philippines, Borneo, the Malay peninsula, and islands in peninsular Thailand and Burma, Sumatra, Java and its satellites, Bali, Lombok, western Sumbawa, Sulawesi, Palauan and Chamorro of western Micronesia, the seven or eight Chamic languages of mainland Southeast Asia and Hainan Island, and Malagasy.

Name: Proto-South Halmahera-West New Guinea
Description: South Halmahera-West New Guinea = the 30‒40 AN languages of southern Halmahera and the northern Bird’s Head peninsula of New Guinea.

Name: Formosan
Description: Unlike these subgroup labels, “Formosan” is used as a cover term for the aboriginal languages of Taiwan which appear to belong to at least nine primary branches of the AN language family. In addition, PWMP may not be a valid subgroup, and some forms that are currently assigned to it may have been found in PMP.
